We've finally evicted the last of the legacy provider docs from terraform.io!
Let's celebrate by purging all memory of them.

The 0.11 docs are now so thoroughly legacy that I don't believe they need a new
destination for their provider links, so I just removed those.

* website: remove old provider docs index

This will require a redirect in the terraform-website repo.

* Apply suggestions from code review

Change-Id: Ia62563b1677b78929b690357a6fa21fd7e85f331","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/2d0c38e8d7958b311e881537cc912b0c5c14d5cd"},{"sha":"8ffd110da5da70096f4fef635fa8ce7611432346","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Feed input tensors only if shape inference requires constant input

Currently, all constants are fed in the InferenceContext regardless of those are required for shape inference or not. This is wasteful and not even feasible for cases involving very large splat constants. It is not possible to create tensors requiring more memory than what is available on the host.

This may require multiple invocation of shape inference functions but this shouldn't add significant overhead as these functions are generally trivial.

Change-Id: Ieb9247a625b995f08058a730b80d131c2f7f4980","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/c276e314b5d83791a50ca9e3a66df9916848dd06"},{"sha":"e074afc4663247f8400f73bcf61547bf10b030d2","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Add canonicalization pattern for tfr.quant_raw_data op

Once the quantization information is stripped, the tensor can be uses as usual and raw_data op can be safely removed. The redundant cast ops with quantized type is not removed by cast op's canonicalization, but they are removed when they have no users after all tfr.quant_raw_data and tfr.quant_qparams ops are canonicalized.

Also moved canonicalization tests into a separate file, while adding a new test for quant_raw_data op.

Change-Id: I072a84fd02738dd2f51b3f42836ed80067dba4a8","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/7bdf50bb4f5c54a4997c379092888546c97c3ebd"},{"sha":"b89b193a6572e4c73da3d396381159aebd3d5abc","author":{"name":"Yunxing Dai","email":"0e6edd405794f4fb8b1584e93c0a178f5c32bc6a@google.com"},"message":"ValueInference -- Simplify expression before evaluating.

Previously we evaluate the expression `upperbound(a+(b-a))` as
`upperbound(a) + upperbound(b - a)`, which is then evaluated as
`upperbound(a) + upperbound(b) - lowerbound(a)`

However this bound can be tighten to upperbound(b) if we do a quick
algebraic simplification on the expression before evaluating.

This is even more useful when lowering a pad op to pad to a static value.

```
size = tf.size(T)[0]
pad_width = MAX_SIZE - size
tf.pad(T, pad_width) # The result size is a static value size + MAX_SIZE - size = MAX_SIZE

Change-Id: I072a84fd02738dd2f51b3f42836ed80067dba4a8","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/7bdf50bb4f5c54a4997c379092888546c97c3ebd"},{"sha":"b89b193a6572e4c73da3d396381159aebd3d5abc","author":{"name":"Yunxing Dai","email":"0e6edd405794f4fb8b1584e93c0a178f5c32bc6a@google.com"},"message":"ValueInference -- Simplify expression before evaluating.

Previously we evaluate the expression `upperbound(a+(b-a))` as
`upperbound(a) + upperbound(b - a)`, which is then evaluated as
`upperbound(a) + upperbound(b) - lowerbound(a)`

However this bound can be tighten to upperbound(b) if we do a quick
algebraic simplification on the expression before evaluating.

This is even more useful when lowering a pad op to pad to a static value.

```
size = tf.size(T)[0]
pad_width = MAX_SIZE - size
tf.pad(T, pad_width) # The result size is a static value size + MAX_SIZE - size = MAX_SIZE
```

[{"sha":"b89b193a6572e4c73da3d396381159aebd3d5abc","author":{"name":"Yunxing Dai","email":"0e6edd405794f4fb8b1584e93c0a178f5c32bc6a@google.com"},"message":"ValueInference -- Simplify expression before evaluating.

Previously we evaluate the expression `upperbound(a+(b-a))` as
`upperbound(a) + upperbound(b - a)`, which is then evaluated as
`upperbound(a) + upperbound(b) - lowerbound(a)`

However this bound can be tighten to upperbound(b) if we do a quick
algebraic simplification on the expression before evaluating.

This is even more useful when lowering a pad op to pad to a static value.

```
size = tf.size(T)[0]
pad_width = MAX_SIZE - size
tf.pad(T, pad_width) # The result size is a static value size + MAX_SIZE - size = MAX_SIZE
```

Change-Id: If8edc9e9bc915eab5a0285a6502a7bf56c6ed10a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YaphetRowe/tensorflow/commits/27c5fa686e0f519e066b6da5118871ab4cb805f7"},{"sha":"103a3aa856caf1b539e9045ed6af4f3cec9015c0","author":{"name":"metarutaiga","email":"79dcb454b3ba32236f0276331d624b4cb6f2e888@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Rename IN / OUT to INPUT / OUTPUT for Windows on ARM","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YaphetRowe/tensorflow/commits/103a3aa856caf1b539e9045ed6af4f3cec9015c0"},{"sha":"7959ae05ec674311ebea4e7ad919c9520bc0f40c","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Short-circuit CAS loop.

When doing a compare-and-swap, if we ever get to the point where `old == new`,
just declare victory and exit.

Previously we'd continue doing the CAS with old == new until it "succeeded".

This particularly helps for scatters that

 - go from a large input to a small output (so there are many "collisions" on a
   given point), and

 - have many "nop" updates, for example with a max op, it's likely that most of
   the time you won't need to do anything because the value in the output is
   already larger.

[{"sha":"feb2f6892ab42a6efc1333bbf1544b7337e8f244","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTool: hook names cache no longer loses entries between selection (#21831)

Made several changes to the hooks name cache to avoid losing cached data between selected elements:
1. No longer use React-managed cache. This had the unfortunate side effect of the inspected element cache also clearing the hook names cache. For now, instead, a module-level WeakMap cache is used. This isn't great but we can revisit it later.

For internal experimentation only.

This implements `unstable_useContextSelector` behind a feature flag.
It's based on [RFC 119](https://github.com/reactjs/rfcs/pull/119) and
[RFC 118](https://github.com/reactjs/rfcs/pull/118) by @gnoff.

Usage:

```js
const context = useContextSelector(Context, c => c.selectedField);
```

The key feature is that if the selected value does not change between
renders, the component will bail out of rendering its children, a la
`memo`, `PureComponent`, or the `useState` bailout mechanism. (Unless
some other state, props, or context was updated in the same render.)

One difference from the RFC is that it does not return the selected
value. It returns the full context object. This serves a few purposes:
it discourages you from creating any new objects or derived values
inside the selector, because it'll get thrown out regardless. Instead,
all the selector will do is return a subfield. Then you can compute
the derived value inside the component, and if needed, you memoize that
derived value with `useMemo`.

If all the selectors do is access a subfield, they're (theoretically)
fast enough that we can call them during the propagation scan and bail
out really early, without having to visit the component during the
render phase.

Another benefit is that it's API compatible with `useContext`. So we can
put it behind a flag that falls back to regular `useContext`.

The longer term vision is that these optimizations (in addition to other
memoization checks, like `useMemo` and `useCallback`) are inserted
automatically by a compiler. So you would write code like this:

```js
const {a, b} = useContext(Context);
const derived = computeDerived(a, b);
```

and it would get converted to something like this:

```js
const {a} = useContextSelector(Context, context => context.a);
const {b} = useContextSelector(Context, context => context.b);
const derived = useMemo(() => computeDerived(a, b), [a, b]);
```

(Though not this exactly. Some lower level compiler output target.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/ae128b32c4493c4bb57451d3df149f211687f628"},{"sha":"85dc024a1ab7555241e13a4b9b2baae44e17328b","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Move API to unstable `useContext` option

This will to make it easier to A/B test, or to revert if we abandon the
experiment. Using a selector will not change the return type of
`useContext`. Use a userspace hook to get the selected value:

```js
function useContextSelector<C, S>(Context: C, selector: C => S): S {
  const context = useContext(Context, {unstable_selector: selector});
  const selectedContext = selector(context);
  return selectedContext;
}
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/85dc024a1ab7555241e13a4b9b2baae44e17328b"},{"sha":"c0b8b589677917184484ced078c28cb8229ada7a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Run selectors during propagation to bail out early","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/c0b8b589677917184484ced078c28cb8229ada7a"}]

[{"sha":"b89b193a6572e4c73da3d396381159aebd3d5abc","author":{"name":"Yunxing Dai","email":"0e6edd405794f4fb8b1584e93c0a178f5c32bc6a@google.com"},"message":"ValueInference -- Simplify expression before evaluating.

Previously we evaluate the expression `upperbound(a+(b-a))` as
`upperbound(a) + upperbound(b - a)`, which is then evaluated as
`upperbound(a) + upperbound(b) - lowerbound(a)`

However this bound can be tighten to upperbound(b) if we do a quick
algebraic simplification on the expression before evaluating.

This is even more useful when lowering a pad op to pad to a static value.

```
size = tf.size(T)[0]
pad_width = MAX_SIZE - size
tf.pad(T, pad_width) # The result size is a static value size + MAX_SIZE - size = MAX_SIZE
```

When doing a compare-and-swap, if we ever get to the point where `old == new`,
just declare victory and exit.

Previously we'd continue doing the CAS with old == new until it "succeeded".

This particularly helps for scatters that

 - go from a large input to a small output (so there are many "collisions" on a
   given point), and

 - have many "nop" updates, for example with a max op, it's likely that most of
   the time you won't need to do anything because the value in the output is
   already larger.

Scheduler's heap implementation sometimes accesses indices that are out

This change fixes the de-opt by always checking the index before

returned element.

This commit contains a proposed change to layout effect semantics within Suspense subtrees: If a component mounts within a Suspense boundary and is later hidden (because of something else suspending) React will cleanup that component’s layout effects (including React-managed refs).

This change will hopefully fix existing bugs that occur because of things like reading layout in a hidden tree and will also enable a point at which to e.g. pause videos and hide user-managed portals. After the suspended boundary resolves, React will setup the component’s layout effects again (including React-managed refs).

The scenario described above is not common. The useTransition API should ensure that Suspense does not revert to its fallback state after being mounted.

Note that these changes are primarily written in terms of the (as of yet internal) Offscreen API as we intend to provide similar effects semantics within recently shown/hidden Offscreen trees in the future. (More to follow.)

(Note that all changes in this PR are behind a new feature flag, enableSuspenseLayoutEffectSemantics, which is disabled for now.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kodgladiator/react/commits/7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7"},{"sha":"d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update build-for-devtools script to prepare unit tests too (#21182)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kodgladiator/react/commits/d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e"},{"sha":"ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Bumped DevTools Chrome and Firefox versions in Babel config (#21185)

We have been building DevTools to target Chrome 49 and Firefox 54. These are super old browser versions and they did not have full ES6 support, so the generated build is more bloated than it needs to be.

DevTools uses most modern language features. Off the top of my head, we it uses basically everything but async and generator functions.

Based on CanIUse charts– I believe that in order to avoid unnecessary polyfill/wrapper code being generated, we'd need to target Chrome 60+ (released 2017-07-25) and Firefox 55+ (released 2017-04-18). This seems like a reasonable set of browsers to target.

Note that we can't remove the IE 11 target from the react-devtools-core backend yet due to Hermes (React Native) ES6 support but that should be doable by the end of the year given current engineering targets. But we could update the frontend target, as well as the targets for the extensions and the react-devtools-inline package.

Change-Id: I072a84fd02738dd2f51b3f42836ed80067dba4a8","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/7bdf50bb4f5c54a4997c379092888546c97c3ebd"},{"sha":"b89b193a6572e4c73da3d396381159aebd3d5abc","author":{"name":"Yunxing Dai","email":"0e6edd405794f4fb8b1584e93c0a178f5c32bc6a@google.com"},"message":"ValueInference -- Simplify expression before evaluating.

Previously we evaluate the expression `upperbound(a+(b-a))` as
`upperbound(a) + upperbound(b - a)`, which is then evaluated as
`upperbound(a) + upperbound(b) - lowerbound(a)`

However this bound can be tighten to upperbound(b) if we do a quick
algebraic simplification on the expression before evaluating.

This is even more useful when lowering a pad op to pad to a static value.

```
size = tf.size(T)[0]
pad_width = MAX_SIZE - size
tf.pad(T, pad_width) # The result size is a static value size + MAX_SIZE - size = MAX_SIZE
```

PiperOrigin-RevId: 383728665
Change-Id: Ie8670ea7a3c1ad5851d93ef70b57a822d2d3bd06","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/24e4c8ec69406b56f900875685aaa939959770f7"},{"sha":"6bd7c7d251719bf6d9894e2fb4b64a208e56d70e","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Fix fused convolutions with cudnn frontend.

Before this patch, fused bias-activation convolutions has two bugs when the
cudnn frontend API is enabled.

 - While autotuning, we always used 0 bytes of scratch memory for each
   algorithm, even if the algorithm called for more than that.  As a result,
   most algorithms failed.

 - After autotuning, we wouldn't call FusedConvolveWithExecutionPlan.  Instead,
   we'd always call FusedConvolveWithAlgorithm.  As a result, even if we had a
   good conv plan from autotuning, we wouldn't use it; instead, we'd use the
   default conv algorithm.

I verified by code inspection that the other kinds of convolutions don't have
this same bug.
